### Tuple Types in C#

Tuples provide a lightweight way to group multiple values without creating a custom class or struct. Value tuples were introduced in C# 7.

### Creating Tuples

```csharp
// Implicitly typed
var person = ("Alice", 30);

// Explicit types
(string, int) person = ("Alice", 30);

// Named elements
(string Name, int Age) person = ("Alice", 30);
var person = (Name: "Alice", Age: 30);
```

### Accessing Tuple Elements

```csharp
var person = (Name: "Alice", Age: 30);

// By name
Console.WriteLine(person.Name);
Console.WriteLine(person.Age);

// By position (Item1, Item2, etc.)
Console.WriteLine(person.Item1);
Console.WriteLine(person.Item2);
```

### Tuples as Return Values

```csharp
// Returning multiple values from a method
static (int Min, int Max) FindMinMax(int[] numbers)
{
    int min = numbers[0];
    int max = numbers[0];

    foreach (var n in numbers)
    {
        if (n < min) min = n;
        if (n > max) max = n;
    }

    return (min, max);
}

// Usage
var result = FindMinMax(new[] { 3, 1, 4, 1, 5, 9 });
Console.WriteLine($"Min: {result.Min}, Max: {result.Max}");
```

### Deconstruction

```csharp
var person = ("Alice", 30);

// Deconstruct into separate variables
var (name, age) = person;
Console.WriteLine($"{name}, {age}");

// Deconstruct with discards
var (name2, _) = person;

// Deconstruct existing variables
(string name3, int age3) = person;
```

### Tuple Equality

```csharp
var t1 = (1, "Alice");
var t2 = (1, "Alice");

Console.WriteLine(t1 == t2);     // True (structural equality)
Console.WriteLine(t1.Equals(t2)); // True
```

### Named Elements in Methods

```csharp
static (string Name, int Age, double Score) GetStudent()
{
    return ("Bob", 20, 85.5);
}

var student = GetStudent();
Console.WriteLine($"{student.Name} scored {student.Score}");
```

### Tuples in LINQ

```csharp
var people = new[]
{
    (Name: "Alice", Age: 30),
    (Name: "Bob", Age: 25),
    (Name: "Charlie", Age: 35)
};

var results = people
    .Where(p => p.Age > 25)
    .Select(p => (p.Name, IsAdult: p.Age >= 18));
```

### Tuple vs Custom Type

| Aspect | Value Tuple | Custom Class/Struct |
|--------|-------------|---------------------|
| Syntax | Lightweight | More code |
| Semantics | No named type | Has a type name |
| Mutation | Mutable by default | Can be immutable |
| Use case | Internal/private APIs | Public API, complex types |

### Tuple Limitations

```csharp
// Up to 7 elements + 1 (8th as nested)
var t = (1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7, (8, 9));
Console.WriteLine(t.Rest.Item1);  // (8, 9)
```

> **Key Point:** Tuples are great for returning multiple values from a method or grouping data temporarily. Use named elements for clarity. Tuples are value types with structural equality. For public APIs, consider defining a custom type for better documentation and maintainability.

### System.Tuple vs ValueTuple

```csharp
// Old reference tuple (System.Tuple)
Tuple<string, int> old = Tuple.Create("Alice", 30);

// New value tuple (ValueTuple) - preferred
(string, int) modern = ("Alice", 30);
```

### Tuples with Deconstruct Methods

```csharp
// Custom deconstruction
public class Point
{
    public int X { get; }
    public int Y { get; }

    public void Deconstruct(out int x, out int y)
    {
        x = X;
        y = Y;
    }
}

var point = new Point { X = 3, Y = 4 };
var (x, y) = point;

codeExample:
using System;

class Program
{
    static void Main()
    {
        var result = Calculate(10, 3);
        Console.WriteLine($"Sum: {result.Sum}, Difference: {result.Diff}");

        // Deconstruction
        var (sum, diff) = Calculate(20, 7);
        Console.WriteLine($"Sum: {sum}, Diff: {diff}");
    }

    static (int Sum, int Diff) Calculate(int a, int b)
    {
        return (a + b, a - b);
    }
}
